english:
  title: A Memorial on Current Affairs
  author: Jung Hyo-bok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant respectfully submits this petition. The tuntian system of land tenure is what all the common people detest together, and women are not fit to be kept in the chambers of eunuchs. If this is not prohibited, how can there be good governance? This is the first matter your servant fails to comprehend.

    Military strength does not depend on numbers alone, but on excellence; officials need not be numerous, only capable. When unnecessary posts multiply and useless soldiers abound, how can the people not suffer hardship? How can the nation not grow poor? This is the second matter your servant fails to comprehend.

    What benefit do Buddhist monks bring to the realm, that they receive official credentials and ride fine horses? What virtue do the Japanese possess toward our people, that we fill their ships with grain and rice during their famines? This is the third matter your servant fails to comprehend.

    Alas, when equal merit receives unequal rewards—this follows the ranks of nobility. When the same crime receives unequal punishments—this bends to kinship and favor. How then can rewards encourage virtue? How can punishments deter wrongdoing? When one man commits crime yet the nation cries for death, and still he lives—how can the people's hearts find peace? With the people's hearts unsettled, how can the nation avoid peril? This is the fourth matter your servant fails to comprehend.

    Alas, governance cannot be perfected in every particular, nor can talent be employed without flaw. How could one address each matter exhaustively? Your servant humbly beseeches Your Majesty: embrace frugality and spare expense to enrich the people's livelihood. Humble your palaces and plain your dress to transform customs. Deem wealth lowly and virtue precious—do not harbor ministers who speak of profit. Strengthen the root and suppress the branches, strictly forbidding the idle and workless. Beyond the regular taxes, accept no tribute. Beyond necessary use, permit no construction. Let all affairs follow ancient precedent; establish no new laws. When performing great ceremonies, do not neglect the people's affairs. Show supreme benevolence by sparing those coerced into wrongdoing. Heed not baseless rumors, employ no uninformed counsel. Do not disparage the wise and seasoned. Read repeatedly the "Seventh Month" from the *Book of Poetry*. Let your mind rest upon the "Without Idleness" chapter from the *Book of Documents*. Take the virtuous deeds of Yao, Shun, Yu, Tang, King Wen, and King Wu of old as your virtuous deeds today. Let the admonitions that Gao Yao, Yi Yin, Fu Yue, and the Duke of Zhao gave their sovereigns become as if you hear them yourself today. Do not rely on wealth and rank. Do not boast of honor and station. Do not trust in the abundance of weapons, the strength of walls, or the steepness of mountain passes. Perpetually harbor a heart of reverent caution. Revere Heaven's mandate and fear the common people.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Tuntian (屯田): A system of military agricultural colonies used to support standing armies and reduce state expenditure on provisions.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The "Seventh Month" (七月): A poem from the *Book of Poetry* that celebrates virtuous rulers and agricultural harmony.'
  - key: ''
    value: '"Without Idleness" (無逸): A chapter from the *Book of Documents* (Zhou section) warning rulers against indolence and excess.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Gao Yao, Yi Yin, Fu Yue, and the Duke of Zhao: Legendary sage-ministers of ancient China renowned for their moral counsel to rulers.'
